    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-03-23T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-03-23T18:00:00-05:00" n="665"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d665">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102 S/1020a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Shanghai (<persName corresp="#p_CES1" type="to"
                            >Cunningham</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-03-23T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 23, 1932—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>114. For the Minister. Shanghai’s 196, March 23, 5 p.m., paragraph 2. The
                    Department is of opinion that neither you nor the Consul General should give any
                    encouragement to the proposal that <persName corresp="#p_RFJ1">Raven</persName>
                    resign as a protest against the outcome of the municipal elections, as such
                    action on his part might add, at a most inopportune time, another complication
                    to the present difficult situation at Shanghai. Inform <persName
                        corresp="#p_CES1">Cunningham</persName>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
